ls Policy. http://www.ott.nih.gov/pdfs/64FR72090.pdf',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(23,0,1,'Performance','',23,'default','The Federal Technology Transfer Act of 1986, 15 U.S.C. § 3710a(d)(1) prohibits {ICD} from providing funds to {Collaborator} to conduct any activities described in the Research Plan under this CRADA.','Should not need this language in a CRADA, but no harm in including it if the CRADA collaborator wants it there.  This is more of a notice and not a term that is conveying any obligation.',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(23,0,2,'Definitions','',23,'default','<B> NIH Sole CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(23,0,3,'Definitions','',23,'default','<B>  Sole CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(23,0,4,'Definitions','',23,'default','<B>  Sole CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(24,0,1,'Performance','',24,'default','{ICD} will not use funds provided by {Collaborator} under this CRADA for {ICD} personnel to pay the salary of any permanent {ICD} employee.  No {ICD} employees will be required to devote 100% of their effort or time to performance of the Research Plan.','Optional when funds are provided to hire staff.  The language provided is just an example or guideline.  This statement is true if it is included or not.  No statements to the contrary can be made in the CRADA. It is statutory that funds cannot be used for FTE positions.  It is NIH Policy that staff being funded not be required to devote 100% of their time to CRADA activities.  NOTE:  Under CRADA statutes, CRADA funds can only be used as specified in the CRADA. Therefore, it is important to address this point.  If funds are being provided and may be used towards costs of staff (contractor, nurse, postdoc, non-FTE), then this needs to specifically spelled out that funds can be used for staff somewhere in the CRADA.  ',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(24,0,2,'Definitions','',24,'default','<B> Joint CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(24,0,3,'Definitions','',24,'default','<B> Joint CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(24,0,4,'Definitions','',24,'default','<B> Joint CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(25,0,1,'Performance','',25,'default','The PIs should exchange information regularly, as required to advance the activities under the Research Plan.    The Parties will exchange final reports of their results within {3-6} months of the expiration or termination of this CRADA. The final report will be a summary of the CRADA Data and will include a summary of all publications, CRADA Subject Inventions, and corresponding patent applications arising from the activities under the Research Plan.  ','The time line for exchange of information is optional and does not need to be included.  If the IC PI or Collaborator request the term, then this statement is provided as a starting point for negotiation.  The final language is negotiable between the parties as is appropriate for the research plan and agreed to by the Parties.  {Optional}  This exchange may be accomplished through e-mail, phone calls, meeting minutes, annual reports, detailed correspondence, and circulation of draft manuscripts.',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(25,0,2,'Definitions','',25,'default','<B> Collaborator Sole CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(25,0,3,'Definitions','',25,'default','<B> Collaborator Sole CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(25,0,4,'Definitions','',25,'default','<B> Collaborator Sole CRADA Subject Invention</B>: undefined',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(26,0,1,'Performance','',26,'default','silent','blank',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(26,0,2,'Definitions','',26,'default','<B> CRADA Software</B>: \"CRADA Software\" means computer readable source code or object code, whether or not compiled, written in whole or in part in the performance of the Research Plan, together with any documentation pertaining to the structure, function, or use thereof or pertaining to the interoperation of said code with other computer readable code.',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(26,0,3,'Definitions','',26,'default','<B> CRADA Software</B>: \"CRADA Software\" means computer readable source code or object code, whether or not compiled, written in whole or in part in the performance of the Research Plan, together with any documentation pertaining to the structure, function, or use thereof or pertaining to the interoperation of said code with other computer readable code.',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(26,0,4,'Definitions','',26,'default','<B> CRADA Software</B>: \"CRADA Software\" means computer readable source code or object code, whether or not compiled, written in whole or in part in the performance of the Research Plan, together with any documentation pertaining to the structure, function, or use thereof or pertaining to the interoperation of said code with other computer readable code.',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(27,0,2,'Performance','',27,'default','PI Cause goes here',NULL,NULL,0,0,1,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(27,0,3,'Performance','',27,'default','PI Cause goes here',NULL,NULL,0,0,1,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(27,0,4,'Performance','',27,'default','PI Cause goes here',NULL,NULL,0,0,1,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(28,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',28,'default','Obligations when Sharing Confidential Information.  Each Party agrees to limit disclosure of its Confidential Information to the other Party to the amount necessary to conduct the activities of the Research Plan.  All information to be deemed confidential under this Agreement shall be clearly marked “CONFIDENTIAL” by the disclosing Party.  Any Confidential Information which is orally disclosed must be reduced to writing in summary form by the disclosing Party.  The disclosing Party must mark the summary as “CONFIDENTIAL” and provide it to the other Party within fifteen (15) days of the original disclosure.','• Since each Party has obligations to maintain the other party\'s Confidential Information in a specific manner, the Parties should only share what is needed to limit the risk of liability.  Being in receipt of more Confidential Information than is needed is burdensome for a receiving party.\n• The marking requirement assists the IC in identifying a CRADA Collaborator’s Confidential Information when there has been a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request.  The marking demonstrates that the Collaborator believes its information is confidential.   If Confidential Information is marked as such, NIH may be able to redact such information under a FOIA exception.  If a CRADA Collaborator does not mark its Confidential Information, it does so at its own risk.\n• In some cases, a Collaborator may not agree to, or strongly prefer not to, mark Confidential Information because it is burdensome.  Another reason a Collaborator may reject the marking requirement is due to the concern that with such a requirement, Confidential Information inadvertently left unmarked would be less likely to be treated as confidential.  The marking language can be modified or replaced with language that encourages marking, but does not exclude unmarked information from being Confidential Information.  \n• In Convolve, Inc. v. Compaq Computer Corp., No. 2012-1074, 2013 WL 3285331 (Fed. Cir. July 1, 2013), a disclosing party failed to comply with marking requirements and lost its trade secret protection. So while marking may help protect a Collaborator’s Confidential Information from release under FOIA, failure to comply with a marking requirement could result in loss of the Confidential Information’s confidential status.\n• Typically, NIH does not accept trade secret information because NIH may be required to keep trade secret information confidential and not disclose it as long as the information is a trade secret. This obligation could interfere with publishing the results of the CRADA research. Per 15 USC section 3710a (c)(7)(A) of the CRADA statute, “No trade secrets or commercial or financial information that is privileged or confidential, under the meaning of section 552 (b)(4) of title 5, which is obtained in the conduct of research or as a result of activities under this chapter from a non-Federal party participating in a cooperative research and development agreement shall be disclosed.”  A CRADA Collaborator should be discouraged from providing trade secret information unless it is truly necessary.  If it is necessary for an IC to accept trade secret information from a CRADA Collaborator, all such information should be clearly marked as a trade secret so that the IC can maintain its obligation.\n',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(28,0,2,'Performance','',28,'default','Research Plan Clause goes here',NULL,NULL,0,0,2,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(28,0,3,'Performance','',28,'default','Research Plan Clause goes here',NULL,NULL,0,0,2,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(28,0,4,'Performance','',28,'default','Research Plan Clause goes here',NULL,NULL,0,0,2,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(29,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',29,'default','Use of Confidential Information.  Each Party agrees to use the other Party’s Confidential Information only for the purpose of conducting the activities of the CRADA.   Each Party agrees to use reasonable efforts to maintain the confidentiality of the other Party’s Confidential Information, which will in no instance be less effort than the receiving Party uses to protect its own Confidential Information. The Parties may share Confidential Information with their Affiliates, agents or contractors for the purposes of conducting the activities of the Research Plan, provided the obligations of this Article are simultaneously conveyed.  Neither Party will disclose or otherwise make available to any other person or entity the other Party’s Confidential Information without the consent of the other Party, except as required by a court or administrative body of competent jurisdiction, law or regulation.  In such a situation, neither Party will be liable for the disclosure of that portion of the other Party’s Confidential Information which, after reasonable notice to and consultation with the disclosing Party, the receiving Party determines may not be lawfully withheld.  The receiving Party will then provide the disclosing Party a reasonable opportunity to seek a court order to enjoin disclosure.  Each Party may retain one (1) copy of the other Party’s Confidential Information for archival purposes.','Caution should be used if agreeing to include timelines for consultations.  A Party may be under a court order or other requirement to produce information within a short deadline. \n\nA Collaborator may request to add language that states a Party is entitled to injunctive relief in the event of an unauthorized disclosure or intended disclosure of Confidential Information. Since a CRADA is a type of contract, it will be subject to the Tucker Act (28 U.S.C. 1491) which provides that contract actions against the Government may only be brought in the Court of Federal Claims and only for money damages.  Therefore, it is generally acceptable to state that a party may seek injunctive relief through the courts.  However, it is not acceptable to state that an unauthorized disclosure of Confidential Information will cause “irreparable harm” for which no adequate remedy at law is available.   Such a statement may suggest that the Parties believe exceptional harm could result beyond what is contemplated by the contract. While it is unlikely that a court would agree, there is no point in raising the issue.  Also the Department of Justice (DOJ) litigates for the Government; thus it is the jurisdiction of DOJ to decide these matters. Finally, most of the discussion involving equitable relief and injunctions is in fact moot because, per the Tucker Act, any claim regarding inappropriate disclosure by the Government of a party’s confidential information would be for money damages, not injunctive relief.  (For a discussion of Tucker Act jurisdiction see United States Marine, Inc. v. United States v. VT Halter Marine, Inc.  2012-1678 (Fed. Cir. July 15, 2013).)\n\nA Collaborator may identify items that may contain Confidential Information that the Collaborator believes should be destroyed, including notes taken by the NIH investigator or other Government documents.  It may be inappropriate to destroy such Government records as such records may be subject to specific rules for their management and destruction.( See: NIH Manual Chapter 1743-Keeping and Destroying Records.)\n',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(29,0,2,'Performance','',29,'default','The activities described under the Research Plan of this CRADA will be carried out under the supervision of the Principal Investigators identified on the Summary Page.','not statutory but good business practice -- ask OGC if this is required by statute and if it needs to say \"carried out by Parties\".',NULL,0,0,3,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(29,0,3,'Performance','',29,'default','The activities described under the Research Plan of this CRADA will be carried out under the supervision of the Principal Investigators identified on the Summary Page.','not statutory but good business practice -- ask OGC if this is required by statute and if it needs to say \"carried out by Parties\".',NULL,0,0,3,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(29,0,4,'Performance','',29,'default','The activities described under the Research Plan of this CRADA will be carried out under the supervision of the Principal Investigators identified on the Summary Page.','not statutory but good business practice -- ask OGC if this is required by statute and if it needs to say \"carried out by Parties\".',NULL,0,0,3,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(30,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',30,'default','Duration of Confidentiality Obligations.  The obligation to maintain the confidentiality of Confidential Information will expire three (3) years after the expiration or termination date of this CRADA.  The Parties may negotiate a separate agreement at the end of this period to extend the confidentiality obligation for specific information. The Parties agree to use reasonable efforts not to disclose CRADA Data and descriptions of CRADA Materials until they are made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7. The Parties agree to maintain the confidentiality of IPI indefinitely.','• The 3 year period of confidentiality in Article 8.6 may be negotiated to a 5 year period per NIH policy. However, per OGC, in extenuating circumstances this period of confidentiality may be negotiated to as long as 10 years.  Technology transfer staff should be able to articulate why this added burden is acceptable to the IC. Note that the period listed in the language begins after the period of time prior to expiration or termination. When justifying a lengthy period of confidentiality, staff should keep in mind that over an extended period, the value of Confidential Information may change.\n\n• A federal employee receiving Confidential Information as part of his/her official duty is obligated under The Trade Secret Act (18 USC 1905) to keep such Confidential Information confidential or be subject to criminal penalties. Since this is a criminal statute an action may not be brought by the Collaborator, only by the Government.\n',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(30,0,2,'Performance','',30,'default','If IBM has received (or will receive) support of any kind from a third party in exchange for rights in any of IBM’s CRADA Subject Inventions, IBM agrees to ensure that its obligations to the third party are consistent with this CRADA.','Statutory requirement.  ICD must ensure that the government retains specific rights; i.e., ICD requires the Collaborator to grant licenses for specific health and safety purposes or public use regulations.  See 15USC§3710a(b)(1)(B)',NULL,0,0,4,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(30,0,3,'Performance','',30,'default','If  has received (or will receive) support of any kind from a third party in exchange for rights in any of ’s CRADA Subject Inventions,  agrees to ensure that its obligations to the third party are consistent with this CRADA.','Statutory requirement.  ICD must ensure that the government retains specific rights; i.e., ICD requires the Collaborator to grant licenses for specific health and safety purposes or public use regulations.  See 15USC§3710a(b)(1)(B)',NULL,0,0,4,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(30,0,4,'Performance','',30,'default','If  has received (or will receive) support of any kind from a third party in exchange for rights in any of ’s CRADA Subject Inventions,  agrees to ensure that its obligations to the third party are consistent with this CRADA.','Statutory requirement.  ICD must ensure that the government retains specific rights; i.e., ICD requires the Collaborator to grant licenses for specific health and safety purposes or public use regulations.  See 15USC§3710a(b)(1)(B)',NULL,0,0,4,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(31,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',31,'default','Publication.  The Parties are encouraged to make the results of the CRADA research publicly available.  Before either Party submits information about the activities conducted under the CRADA Research Plan for public disclosure, the other Party will have thirty (30) days to review the proposed disclosure to assure that it does not include that Party’s Confidential Information.  Either Party may request in writing that the disclosure be delayed for up to thirty (30) additional days as necessary to file a patent application. ','• Generally, the IC bias is to publish data generated in research projects in a timely manner.  (See:   “Guidelines for the Conduct of Research in the Intramural Research Program at NIH”; PHS Technology Transfer Policy Manual, Chapter 400, CRADA Policy) In the private sector, this is not as much of a concern.  Once a proposed publication resulting from a CRADA project is complete, NIH policy is not to delay submission for publication.  Collaborators often request that submission of proposed publications be delayed for more than 30 days. If additional review time or delay time is negotiated, the IC Investigator\'s approval is important.  As a general rule, the review and delay time should not exceed 90 days.  \n• The FTTA gives the IC the ability to maintain in confidence CRADA Data for five years from the date of development of that data (15 USC 3710a(c)(7)(B) – see below).  In such an instance, the CRADA Data must be such that it would have the characteristic of being privileged or confidential trade secret or commercial or financial information had it been obtained from a non-Federal party.  This provision in the law can be interpreted to shield unpublished CRADA Data from FOIA requests. If agreeing to delay of CRADA Data, the IC must balance the delay against the NIH policy to publish and must clearly articulate its reason for agreeing to do so.  \n• 15 USC 3710a(c)(7)(B):  “The director, or in the case of a contractor-operated laboratory, the agency, for a period of up to 5 years after development of information that results from research and development activities conducted under this chapter and that would be a trade secret or commercial or financial information that is privileged or confidential if the information had been obtained from a non-Federal party participating in a cooperative research and development agreement, may provide appropriate protections against the dissemination of such information, including exemption from subchapter II of chapter 5 of title 5.”\n• Sometimes CRADA research is performed where the IC is only one site of a multi-site study organized by the Collaborator.  In such cases, the Collaborator may prefer to include language acknowledging that the first publication will be one to which all sites will contribute.  ICs can agree to this, assuming it is acceptable to the IC investigator.  Alternative language can be used that states this and includes an outer limit to how long the IC agrees to delay publication of the research results.\n',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(31,0,2,'Performance','',31,'default','Any IBM employees who will work at NIH facilities will be required to sign an appropriate agreement in view of the terms of this CRADA.','optional language for use when Collaborator employee will be working at ICD.  There is currently no official PHS guest researcher or special volunteer agreement that is specific for CRADAs.  Consult OGC if Collaborator asks for a specific agreement to be included as an Appendix.',NULL,0,0,5,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(31,0,3,'Performance','',31,'default','Any  employees who will work at  facilities will be required to sign an appropriate agreement in view of the terms of this CRADA.','optional language for use when Collaborator employee will be working at ICD.  There is currently no official PHS guest researcher or special volunteer agreement that is specific for CRADAs.  Consult OGC if Collaborator asks for a specific agreement to be included as an Appendix.',NULL,0,0,5,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(31,0,4,'Performance','',31,'default','Any  employees who will work at  facilities will be required to sign an appropriate agreement in view of the terms of this CRADA.','optional language for use when Collaborator employee will be working at ICD.  There is currently no official PHS guest researcher or special volunteer agreement that is specific for CRADAs.  Consult OGC if Collaborator asks for a specific agreement to be included as an Appendix.',NULL,0,0,5,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(32,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',32,'default','Right of Access to and Use of CRADA Data.  The Parties agree to exchange all CRADA Data and to use reasonable efforts to limit disclosure of CRADA Data until made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7.  CRADA Data shall be jointly-owned, and both Parties will be free to use CRADA Data for any lawful purpose.  The Parties may share CRADA Data with their Affiliates, agents or contractors for the purposes of carrying out the Research Plan provided the obligations of this CRADA are simultaneously conveyed.','As stated in the comments for the definition of Confidential Information, CRADA Data is not treated as Confidential Information; rather disclosure of CRADA Data is limited until it is made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7. If such information were inadvertently classified as Confidential Information, a dispute with the Collaborator might arise when the IC is ready to publish it. \n\nAgreeing in the CRADA that both Parties will have access and use of the CRADA Data (versus either Party owning the CRADA Data) is in keeping with the spirit of collaboration.  However, this does not mean that the Parties may not seek patent protection or copyright registration for CRADA Data.  When negotiating language about data use, staff should consider what is fair in the context of the specific collaboration and balance it against the needs of the IC.  For example, an IC agreeing that a CRADA Collaborator has exclusive use of CRADA Data from clinical studies for regulatory purposes may be reasonable when the Collaborator is the owner of the investigational agent being studied.  Once CRADA Data is published, the issue of use and access is mostly moot.\n',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(32,0,2,'Performance','',32,'default','The Parties agree to use Collaborator Materials and ICD Materials in accordance with activities described under the Research Plan.  The Parties further agree to retain control over these materials and will not transfer these materials to third parties, without advance written approval of the providing Party.  Upon expiration or termination of the CRADA, each Party agrees to dispose of these materials as directed by the owning or providing Party.','This is standard language that would be used in any MTA.  This is good business practice.  This is a good starting point for negotiations but may be modified as needed to fit the needs of the IC and Collaborator to carry out the Research Plan.  Optional--to add -- \"Upon notice of termination, the Parties will devise a plan for sharing and distribution of CRADA Materials and CRADA Data.\" If you anticipate creating CRADA Materials (such as mice, antibodies, etc), this sentence may used as a starting point for negotiations so that you don\'t have to settle the plan before you even know the value of the CRADA Materials or CRADA Data.',NULL,0,0,6,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(32,0,3,'Performance','',32,'default','The Parties agree to use Collaborator Materials and ICD Materials in accordance with activities described under the Research Plan.  The Parties further agree to retain control over these materials and will not transfer these materials to third parties, without advance written approval of the providing Party.  Upon expiration or termination of the CRADA, each Party agrees to dispose of these materials as directed by the owning or providing Party.','This is standard language that would be used in any MTA.  This is good business practice.  This is a good starting point for negotiations but may be modified as needed to fit the needs of the IC and Collaborator to carry out the Research Plan.  Optional--to add -- \"Upon notice of termination, the Parties will devise a plan for sharing and distribution of CRADA Materials and CRADA Data.\" If you anticipate creating CRADA Materials (such as mice, antibodies, etc), this sentence may used as a starting point for negotiations so that you don\'t have to settle the plan before you even know the value of the CRADA Materials or CRADA Data.',NULL,0,0,6,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(32,0,4,'Performance','',32,'default','The Parties agree to use Collaborator Materials and ICD Materials in accordance with activities described under the Research Plan.  The Parties further agree to retain control over these materials and will not transfer these materials to third parties, without advance written approval of the providing Party.  Upon expiration or termination of the CRADA, each Party agrees to dispose of these materials as directed by the owning or providing Party.','This is standard language that would be used in any MTA.  This is good business practice.  This is a good starting point for negotiations but may be modified as needed to fit the needs of the IC and Collaborator to carry out the Research Plan.  Optional--to add -- \"Upon notice of termination, the Parties will devise a plan for sharing and distribution of CRADA Materials and CRADA Data.\" If you anticipate creating CRADA Materials (such as mice, antibodies, etc), this sentence may used as a starting point for negotiations so that you don\'t have to settle the plan before you even know the value of the CRADA Materials or CRADA Data.',NULL,0,0,6,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(33,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',33,'default','Ownership of CRADA Materials.  The producing Party will retain sole ownership of and title to all CRADA Materials produced solely by its employee(s) (Sole CRADA Materials), and the Parties will own jointly all CRADA Materials developed jointly (Joint CRADA Materials).  For clarity, the Parties acknowledge that any CRADA Materials produced by one of the Parties and incorporating materials owned by the other Party shall be considered Joint CRADA Materials.','It is very easy to visualize one Party creating a Sole CRADA Material de novo and both Parties creating a Joint CRADA Material together de novo.  The complicating feature of CRADA Materials is when a new CRADA Material has one of the Party\'s originally provided Materials embedded in it.  For example, the IC being the only pair of hands that added a gene of interest to the CRADA Collaborator\'s expression vector.  In the true spirit of collaboration, such CRADA Materials are being defined as Joint CRADA Materials.',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(33,0,2,'Performance','',33,'default','This CRADA shall be effective upon execution by the Parties and will be in force for the term set forth on the Summary Page. The term may be extended and the provisions of this CRADA may be modified only by amendment signed by the duly authorized signatory for each Party. This Agreement may be terminated by either Party for any reason by providing written notice at least thirty (30) days prior to the desired termination date.','All CRADAs must have a term limit and will not be approved without one. It is preferable by NIH that the term be specified in the Summary Page, but if requested by the Collaborator, the actual term can be added to this clause.  For example, the first sentence could say \"This CRADA shall be effective upon execution by the Parties and will be in force for the term of X years.\"  CRADAs typically have a term of 1-5 years.  You should consider using the upper limit for the term to avoid amendments if possible and agreeable by the Collaborator.  It is easier to terminate than to amend.  Under NIH Policy, the CRADA can only be extended or modified by formal amendment and therefore the second sentence is required.  It is good business practice to address termination and therefore the last sentence is strongly recommended.',NULL,0,0,7,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(33,0,3,'Performance','',33,'default','This CRADA shall be effective upon execution by the Parties and will be in force for the term set forth on the Summary Page. The term may be extended and the provisions of this CRADA may be modified only by amendment signed by the duly authorized signatory for each Party. This Agreement may be terminated by either Party for any reason by providing written notice at least thirty (30) days prior to the desired termination date.','All CRADAs must have a term limit and will not be approved without one. It is preferable by NIH that the term be specified in the Summary Page, but if requested by the Collaborator, the actual term can be added to this clause.  For example, the first sentence could say \"This CRADA shall be effective upon execution by the Parties and will be in force for the term of X years.\"  CRADAs typically have a term of 1-5 years.  You should consider using the upper limit for the term to avoid amendments if possible and agreeable by the Collaborator.  It is easier to terminate than to amend.  Under NIH Policy, the CRADA can only be extended or modified by formal amendment and therefore the second sentence is required.  It is good business practice to address termination and therefore the last sentence is strongly recommended.',NULL,0,0,7,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(33,0,4,'Performance','',33,'default','This CRADA shall be effective upon execution by the Parties and will be in force for the term set forth on the Summary Page. The term may be extended and the provisions of this CRADA may be modified only by amendment signed by the duly authorized signatory for each Party. This Agreement may be terminated by either Party for any reason by providing written notice at least thirty (30) days prior to the desired termination date.','All CRADAs must have a term limit and will not be approved without one. It is preferable by NIH that the term be specified in the Summary Page, but if requested by the Collaborator, the actual term can be added to this clause.  For example, the first sentence could say \"This CRADA shall be effective upon execution by the Parties and will be in force for the term of X years.\"  CRADAs typically have a term of 1-5 years.  You should consider using the upper limit for the term to avoid amendments if possible and agreeable by the Collaborator.  It is easier to terminate than to amend.  Under NIH Policy, the CRADA can only be extended or modified by formal amendment and therefore the second sentence is required.  It is good business practice to address termination and therefore the last sentence is strongly recommended.',NULL,0,0,7,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(34,0,1,'Data & Materials','Default',34,'default','Right of Access to and Use of CRADA Materials.   For the activities of the Research Plan:  The Parties agree to share all CRADA Materials needed to conduct the activities of the Research Plan.  The Parties may share CRADA Materials with their Affiliates, agents or contractors for the purposes of conducting the activities of the Research Plan provided the obligations of this CRADA convey.  Outside the scope of the Research Plan:  After public disclosure about Sole CRADA Materials in accordance with Article 8.7 and consistent with any obligations under this CRADA, a producing Party may use or transfer to any third party its Sole CRADA Materials.  The Parties acknowledge that any transfer of Sole CRADA Materials to the other Party will be at the sole discretion of the owner and may require a separate agreement.  Upon request, each Party will provide reasonable quantities of Joint CRADA Materials to the other Party if reasonably practicable.  Each Party may use Joint CRADA Materials for any purpose provided such use is consistent with any obligations under this CRADA.  After public disclosure about Joint CRADA Materials in accordance with Article 8.7 and consistent with any obligations under this CRADA, either Party may share Joint CRADA Materials with third parties.  However, if a Party shares Joint CRADA Materials with a third party for a commercial purpose, that Party will first inform the other Party.  ','The language provided should be considered a starting point by anyone negotiating a CRADA and may not be appropriate for all projects.  The specialist crafting this language should take into account the specific research project and the needs of the Parties and allow such factors to dictate the sharing flexibility or restrictions that will go forward.  Note that for the language about sharing Sole CRADA Materials or Joint CRADA Materials for research outside the scope of the Research Plan, the phrase \"consistent with any obligations under this CRADA\" is used.  This phrase may have particular meaning in situations where a new CRADA Material has one of the Party’s originally provided Materials embedded in it. An example of such a situation is where the IC is the only pair of hands that added a gene of interest to the CRADA Collaborator’s expression vector.  In the true spirit of collaboration, such CRADA Materials are being defined as Joint CRADA Materials.  In such situations, the specialist crafting the agreement may wish to articulate obligations surrounding a providing Party\'s starting material.  ',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(34,0,2,'Performance','',34,'default','Any dispute arising under this CRADA which is not disposed of by agreement of the Principal Investigators will be submitted jointly to the signatories of this CRADA.  If the signatories, or their designees, are unable to jointly resolve the dispute within thirty (30) days after notification thereof, the Assistant Secretary for Health (or his/her designee or successor) will propose a resolution.  Nothing in this paragraph will prevent any Party from pursuing any additional administrative remedies that may be available and, after exhaustion of such administrative remedies, pursuing all available judicial remedies.  Pending the resolution of any dispute or claim pursuant to this Article, the Parties agree that performance of all obligations will be pursued diligently.','This section is not statutory. However, it is good business practice to include how disputes will be resolved.  This language is a good point for starting negotiations and is recommended by OGC.  If Collaborator request changes, please be aware that some language is not allowed as a Federal Entity.  *Note that a common, unacceptable modification requested by companies is the following:  “ICD recognizes and agrees that there is no adequate remedy at law for any breach of its obligations hereunder…” Switching this statement to read:  “ICD recognizes and agrees that there MAY BE no adequate remedy at law for any breach of its obligations hereunder…” makes this acceptable.  Companies also commonly request that ICD agree to provide “equitable relief” or “judicial relief” in advance.  This is unacceptable; we may not agree to a specific remedy in advance.  Department of Justice (DOJ) is responsible for litigating cases for ICD.',NULL,0,0,8,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(34,0,3,'Performance','',34,'default','Any dispute arising under this CRADA which is not disposed of by agreement of the Principal Investigators will be submitted jointly to the signatories of this CRADA.  If the signatories, or their designees, are unable to jointly resolve the dispute within thirty (30) days after notification thereof, the Assistant Secretary for Health (or his/her designee or successor) will propose a reso