h is an agency within the Department of Health and Human Services (“HHS”) and the “{Collaborator_Full}”, having a principal place of business at ___, and incorporated under the laws of ________.',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(43,0,2,'Performance','',43,'default','The PIs should exchange information regularly, as required to advance the activities under the Research Plan.    The Parties will exchange final reports of their results within {3-6} months of the expiration or termination of this CRADA. The final report will be a summary of the CRADA Data and will include a summary of all publications, CRADA Subject Inventions, and corresponding patent applications arising from the activities under the Research Plan.  ','The time line for exchange of information is optional and does not need to be included.  If the IC PI or Collaborator request the term, then this statement is provided as a starting point for negotiation.  The final language is negotiable between the parties as is appropriate for the research plan and agreed to by the Parties.  {Optional}  This exchange may be accomplished through e-mail, phone calls, meeting minutes, annual reports, detailed correspondence, and circulation of draft manuscripts.',NULL,0,0,17,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(43,0,3,'Performance','',43,'default','The PIs should exchange information regularly, as required to advance the activities under the Research Plan.    The Parties will exchange final reports of their results within {3-6} months of the expiration or termination of this CRADA. The final report will be a summary of the CRADA Data and will include a summary of all publications, CRADA Subject Inventions, and corresponding patent applications arising from the activities under the Research Plan.  ','The time line for exchange of information is optional and does not need to be included.  If the IC PI or Collaborator request the term, then this statement is provided as a starting point for negotiation.  The final language is negotiable between the parties as is appropriate for the research plan and agreed to by the Parties.  {Optional}  This exchange may be accomplished through e-mail, phone calls, meeting minutes, annual reports, detailed correspondence, and circulation of draft manuscripts.',NULL,0,0,17,0,0,'admin','2015-01-06 14:15:47',NULL),(43,0,4,'Performance','',43,'default','The PIs should exchange information regularly, as required to advance the activities under the Research Plan.    The Parties will exchange final reports of their results within {3-6} months of the expiration or termination of this CRADA. The final report will be a summary of the CRADA Data and will include a summary of all publications, CRADA Subject Inventions, and corresponding patent applications arising from the activities under the Research Plan.  ','The time line for exchange of information is optional and does not need to be included.  If the IC PI or Collaborator request the term, then this statement is provided as a starting point for negotiation.  The final language is negotiable between the parties as is appropriate for the research plan and agreed to by the Parties.  {Optional}  This exchange may be accomplished through e-mail, phone calls, meeting minutes, annual reports, detailed correspondence, and circulation of draft manuscripts.',NULL,0,0,17,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(44,0,1,'Legal','Preamble',44,'default','The official contacts for the Parties are identified on the Contacts Information Page.  Publicly available information regarding this CRADA appears on the Summary Page.  ',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(44,0,2,'Data & Materials','',44,'default','Obligations when Sharing Confidential Information.  Each Party agrees to limit disclosure of its Confidential Information to the other Party to the amount necessary to conduct the activities of the Research Plan.  All information to be deemed confidential under this Agreement shall be clearly marked “CONFIDENTIAL” by the disclosing Party.  Any Confidential Information which is orally disclosed must be reduced to writing in summary form by the disclosing Party.  The disclosing Party must mark the summary as “CONFIDENTIAL” and provide it to the other Party within fifteen (15) days of the original disclosure.','• Since each Party has obligations to maintain the other party\'s Confidential Information in a specific manner, the Parties should only share what is needed to limit the risk of liability.  Being in receipt of more Confidential Information than is needed is burdensome for a receiving party.\n• The marking requirement assists the IC in identifying a CRADA Collaborator’s Confidential Information when there has been a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request.  The marking demonstrates that the Collaborator believes its information is confidential.   If Confidential Information is marked as such, NIH may be able to redact such information under a FOIA exception.  If a CRADA Collaborator does not mark its Confidential Information, it does so at its own risk.\n• In some cases, a Collaborator may not agree to, or strongly prefer not to, mark Confidential Information because it is burdensome.  Another reason a Collaborator may reject the marking requirement is due to the concern that with such a requirement, Confidential Information inadvertently left unmarked would be less likely to be treated as confidential.  The marking language can be modified or replaced with language that encourages marking, but does not exclude unmarked information from being Confidential Information.  \n• In Convolve, Inc. v. Compaq Computer Corp., No. 2012-1074, 2013 WL 3285331 (Fed. Cir. July 1, 2013), a disclosing party failed to comply with marking requirements and lost its trade secret protection. So while marking may help protect a Collaborator’s Confidential Information from release under FOIA, failure to comply with a marking requirement could result in loss of the Confidential Information’s confidential status.\n• Typically, NIH does not accept trade secret information because NIH may be required to keep trade secret information confidential and not disclose it as long as the information is a trade secret. This obligation could interfere with publishing the results of the CRADA research. Per 15 USC section 3710a (c)(7)(A) of the CRADA statute, “No trade secrets or commercial or financial information that is privileged or confidential, under the meaning of section 552 (b)(4) of title 5, which is obtained in the conduct of research or as a result of activities under this chapter from a non-Federal party participating in a cooperative research and development agreement shall be disclosed.”  A CRADA Collaborator should be discouraged from providing trade secret information unless it is truly necessary.  If it is necessary for an IC to accept trade secret information from a CRADA Collaborator, all such information should be clearly marked as a trade secret so that the IC can maintain its obligation.\n',NULL,0,0,18,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(44,0,3,'Data & Materials','',44,'default','Obligations when Sharing Confidential Information.  Each Party agrees to limit disclosure of its Confidential Information to the other Party to the amount necessary to conduct the activities of the Research Plan.  All information to be deemed confidential under this Agreement shall be clearly marked “CONFIDENTIAL” by the disclosing Party.  Any Confidential Information which is orally disclosed must be reduced to writing in summary form by the disclosing Party.  The disclosing Party must mark the summary as “CONFIDENTIAL” and provide it to the other Party within fifteen (15) days of the original disclosure.','• Since each Party has obligations to maintain the other party\'s Confidential Information in a specific manner, the Parties should only share what is needed to limit the risk of liability.  Being in receipt 