4',NULL),(45,0,1,'Legal','Preamble',45,'default','The activities undertaken by {ICD} and {Collaborator} in the course of this CRADA are detailed in the Research Plan.  If a definition of a term as provided in this Article conflicts with the definition in the applicable sections of either the United States Code (U.S.C.) or the Code of Federal Regulations (C.F.R.), the definition in the U.S.C. or C.F.R. will control.',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(45,0,2,'Data & Materials','',45,'default','Use of Confidential Information.  Each Party agrees to use the other Party’s Confidential Information only for the purpose of conducting the activities of the CRADA.   Each Party agrees to use reasonable efforts to maintain the confidentiality of the other Party’s Confidential Information, which will in no instance be less effort than the receiving Party uses to protect its own Confidential Information. The Parties may share Confidential Information with their Affiliates, agents or contractors for the purposes of conducting the activities of the Research Plan, provided the obligations of this Article are simultaneously conveyed.  Neither Party will disclose or otherwise make available to any other person or entity the other Party’s Confidential Information without the consent of the other Party, except as required by a court or administrative body of competent jurisdiction, law or regulation.  In such a situation, neither Party will be liable for the disclosure of that portion of the other Party’s Confidential Information which, after reasonable notice to and consultation with the disclosing Party, the receiving Party determines may not be lawfully withheld.  The receiving Party will then provide the disclosing Party a reasonable opportunity to seek a court order to enjoin disclosure.  Each Party may retain one (1) copy of the other Party’s Confidential Information for archival purposes.','Caution should be used if agreeing to include timelines for consultations.  A Party may be under a court order or other requirement to produce information within a short deadline. \n\nA Collaborator may request to add language that states a Party is entitled to injunctive relief in the event of an unauthorized disclosure or intended disclosure of Confidential Information. Since a CRADA is a type of contract, it will be subject to the Tucker Act (28 U.S.C. 1491) which provides that contract actions against the Government may only be brought in the Court of Federal Claims and only for money damages.  Therefore, it is generally acceptable to state that a party may seek injunctive relief through the courts.  However, it is not acceptable to state that an unauthorized disclosure of Confidential Information will cause “irreparable harm” for which no adequate remedy at law is available.   Such a statement may suggest that the Parties believe exceptional harm could result beyond what is contemplated by the contract. While it is unlikely that a court would agree, there is no point in raising the issue.  Also the Department of Justice (DOJ) litigates for the Government; thus it is the jurisdiction of DOJ to decide these matters. Finally, most of the discussion involving equitable relief and injunctions is in fact moot because, per the Tucker Act, any claim regarding inappropriate disclosure by the Government of a party’s confidential information would be for money damages, not injunctive relief.  (For a discussion of Tucker Act jurisdiction see United States Marine, Inc. v. United States v. VT Halter Marine, Inc.  2012-1678 (Fed. Cir. July 15, 2013).)\n\nA Collaborator may identify items that may contain Confidential Information that the Collaborator believes should be destroyed, including notes taken by the NIH investigator or other Government documents.  It may be inappropriate to destroy such Government records as such records may be subject to specific rules for their management and destruction.( See: NIH Manual Chapter 1743-Keepin