ate remedy at law is available.   Such a statement may suggest that the Parties believe exceptional harm could result beyond what is contemplated by the contract. While it is unlikely that a court would agree, there is no point in raising the issue.  Also the Department of Justice (DOJ) litigates for the Government; thus it is the jurisdiction of DOJ to decide these matters. Finally, most of the discussion involving equitable relief and injunctions is in fact moot because, per the Tucker Act, any claim regarding inappropriate disclosure by the Government of a party’s confidential information would be for money damages, not injunctive relief.  (For a discussion of Tucker Act jurisdiction see United States Marine, Inc. v. United States v. VT Halter Marine, Inc.  2012-1678 (Fed. Cir. July 15, 2013).)\n\nA Collaborator may identify items that may contain Confidential Information that the Collaborator believes should be destroyed, including notes taken by the NIH investigator or other Government documents.  It may be inappropriate to destroy such Government records as such records may be subject to specific rules for their management and destruction.( See: NIH Manual Chapter 1743-Keeping and Destroying Records.)\n',NULL,0,0,19,0,0,'all-user','2015-01-06 17:55:54',NULL),(46,0,1,'Legal','Default',46,'default','The construction, validity, performance and effect of this CRADA will be governed by U.S. federal law, as applied by the federal courts in the District of Columbia.  If any provision in this CRADA conflicts with or is inconsistent with any U.S. federal law or regulation, then the U.S. federal law or regulation will preempt that provision.',NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:36:31',NULL),(46,0,2,'Data & Materials','',46,'default','Duration of Confidentiality Obligations.  The obligation to maintain the confidentiality of Confidential Information will expire three (3) years after the expiration or termination date of this CRADA.  The Parties may negotiate a separate agreement at the end of this period to extend the confidentiality obligation for specific information. The Parties agree to use reasonable efforts not to disclose CRADA Data and descriptions of CRADA Materials until they are made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7. The Parties agree to maintain the confidentiality of IPI indefinitely.','• The 3 year period of confidentiality in Article 8.6 may be negotiated to a 5 year period per NIH policy. However, per OGC, in extenuating circumstances this period of confidentiality may be negotiated to as long as 10 years.  Technology transfer staff should be able to articulate why this added burden is acceptable to the IC. Note that the period listed in the language begins after the period of time prior to expiration or termination. When justifying a lengthy period of confidentiality, staff should keep in mind that over an extended period, the value of Confidential Information may change.\n\n• A federal employee receiving Confidential Information as part of his/her official duty is obligated under The Trade Secret Act (18 USC 1905) to keep such Confidential Information confidential or be subject to criminal penalties. Since this is a criminal statute an action may not be brought by the Collaborator, only by the Government.\n',NULL,0,0,20,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(46,0,3,'Data & Materials','',46,'default','Duration of Confidentiality Obligations.  The obligation to maintain the confidentiality of Confidential Information will expire three (3) years after the expiration or termination date of this CRADA.  The Parties may negotiate a separate agreement at the end of this period to extend the confidentiality obligation for specific information. The Parties agree to use reasonable efforts not to disclose CRADA Data and descriptions of CRADA Materials until they are made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7. The Parties agree to maintain the confidentiality of IPI indefinitely.','