me or delay time is negotiated, the IC Investigator\'s approval is important.  As a general rule, the review and delay time should not exceed 90 days.  \n• The FTTA gives the IC the ability to maintain in confidence CRADA Data for five years from the date of development of that data (15 USC 3710a(c)(7)(B) – see below).  In such an instance, the CRADA Data must be such that it would have the characteristic of being privileged or confidential trade secret or commercial or financial information had it been obtained from a non-Federal party.  This provision in the law can be interpreted to shield unpublished CRADA Data from FOIA requests. If agreeing to delay of CRADA Data, the IC must balance the delay against the NIH policy to publish and must clearly articulate its reason for agreeing to do so.  \n• 15 USC 3710a(c)(7)(B):  “The director, or in the case of a contractor-operated laboratory, the agency, for a period of up to 5 years after development of information that results from research and development activities conducted under this chapter and that would be a trade secret or commercial or financial information that is privileged or confidential if the information had been obtained from a non-Federal party participating in a cooperative research and development agreement, may provide appropriate protections against the dissemination of such information, including exemption from subchapter II of chapter 5 of title 5.”\n• Sometimes CRADA research is performed where the IC is only one site of a multi-site study organized by the Collaborator.  In such cases, the Collaborator may prefer to include language acknowledging that the first publication will be one to which all sites will contribute.  ICs can agree to this, assuming it is acceptable to the IC investigator.  Alternative language can be used that states this and includes an outer limit to how long the IC agrees to delay publication of the research results.\n',NULL,0,0,21,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),