ration.  However, this does not mean that the Parties may not seek patent protection or copyright registration for CRADA Data.  When negotiating language about data use, staff should consider what is fair in the context of the specific collaboration and balance it against the needs of the IC.  For example, an IC agreeing that a CRADA Collaborator has exclusive use of CRADA Data from clinical studies for regulatory purposes may be reasonable when the Collaborator is the owner of the investigational agent being studied.  Once CRADA Data is published, the issue of use and access is mostly moot.\n',NULL,0,0,22,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(48,0,3,'Data & Materials','',48,'default','Right of Access to and Use of CRADA Data.  The Parties agree to exchange all CRADA Data and to use reasonable efforts to limit disclosure of CRADA Data until made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7.  CRADA Data shall be jointly-owned, and both Parties will be free to use CRADA Data for any lawful purpose.  The Parties may share CRADA Data with their Affiliates, agents or contractors for the purposes of carrying out the Research Plan provided the obligations of this CRADA are simultaneously conveyed.','As stated in the comments for the definition of Confidential Information, CRADA Data is not treated as Confidential Information; rather disclosure of CRADA Data is limited until it is made publicly available in accordance with Article 8.7. If such information were inadvertently classified as Confidential Information, a dispute with the Collaborator might arise when the IC is ready to publish it. \n\nAgreeing in the CRADA that both Parties will have access and use of the CRADA Data (versus either Party owning the CRADA Data) is in keeping with the spirit of collaboration.  However, this does not mean that the Parties may not seek patent protection or copyright registration for CRADA Data.  When negotiating language about data use, staff should consider what is fair in th