shares Joint CRADA Materials with a third party for a commercial purpose, that Party will first inform the other Party.  ','The language provided should be considered a starting point by anyone negotiating a CRADA and may not be appropriate for all projects.  The specialist crafting this language should take into account the specific research project and the needs of the Parties and allow such factors to dictate the sharing flexibility or restrictions that will go forward.  Note that for the language about sharing Sole CRADA Materials or Joint CRADA Materials for research outside the scope of the Research Plan, the phrase \"consistent with any obligations under this CRADA\" is used.  This phrase may have particular meaning in situations where a new CRADA Material has one of the Party’s originally provided Materials embedded in it. An example of such a situation is where the IC is the only pair of hands that added a gene of interest to the CRADA Collaborator’s expression vector.  In the true spirit of collaboration, such CRADA Materials are being defined as Joint CRADA Materials.  In such situations, the specialist crafting the agreement may wish to articulate obligations surrounding a providing Party\'s starting material.  ',NULL,0,0,24,0,0,'admin','2015-01-05 15:38:08',NULL),(50,0,3,'Data & Materials','',50,'default','Right of Access to and Use of CRADA Materials.   For the activities of the Research Plan:  The Parties agree to share all CRADA Materials needed to conduct the activities of the Research Plan.  The Parties may share CRADA Materials with their Affiliates, agents or contractors for the purposes of conducting the activities of the Research Plan provided the obligations of this CRADA convey.  Outside the scope of the Research Plan:  After public disclosure about Sole CRADA Materials in accordance with Article 8.7 and consistent with any obligations under this CRADA, a producing Party may use or transfer to any third party its Sole CRADA Materials.  The Pa