see. See 37 CFR §404.5(a)(1)\n\nThe Collaborator can apply for any fields of use but will need to show their plan for development or marketing (37 CFR §404.8(h)) in order to get all the fields of use in the license application.\n\nAdditionally, exclusive licenses to non-CRADA Subject Inventions or fields of use not contemplated in the Research Plan are available to the collaborator, but the notice of NIH’s intent to grant the license must be published in the Federal Register. See 37 CFR 404.7(a)(1)\n\n37 CFR § 404 contains regulations related to licensing of government owned inventions.  This explains how the Collaborator exercises its option. OTT will file a patent application and make a CRADA Subject Invention Determination shortly thereafter and then notify the Collaborator if there is a Sole NIH Invention or if NIH is taking responsibility for prosecuting a Joint Invention.\nThis explains what is considered “written notice\" to exercise the option to a commercialization license.  OTT will negotiate the license with the Collaborator as long as the Collaborator is actively and in good faith negotiating.\n\nIf the negotiations end without the Collaborator receiving an exclusive license, then NIH is free to find another licensee. If another company applies for an exclusive commercialization license, the intent to grant will be published, as required by statute, in the Federal Register. In addition, OTT notifies the Collaborator that another company has applied for an exclusive license and the Collaborator has the opportunity to apply or reapply at that time. The Collaborator will always be made aware that the NIH’s rights to the NIH Sole or Joint Invention areas being considered for exclusive licensing to another company.\n\nTherefore, there is no need for the Collaborator to add the old language that gives them the right of first refusal for 6 or more months. The inclusion of that clause makes it impossible for OTT to market the technology as companies do not want 